Nicholson notes that the neumes on fol. 56 are in a lighter ink than the main text and that an ink of the same colour was used by a corrector on fol. 44v who seems to be roughly contemporary with the main scribe. The similarity in the colour of the ink leads Nicholson to speculate that it may have been the corrector who added the neumes. Nicholson reports H. M. Bannister's opinion that the neumes are from Metz, with Bannister noting the similarity with those found in a 12th century antiphon in honour of the Belgian saint Lambert on fol. 155 of . Bannister compares MS. D'Orville 145 to Vatican MS. , fol. 1r, also from St Peter's, Ghent, which has the same lines and similar neumes but repeated throughout the poem ( [1913], vol. 3, p. lxxix). See also Henry Marriott Bannister, (Lipsia, 1913), p. 101, note 2 MS. Auct. T. 2. 23 Reg. lat. 1987 Some of the Oldest Latin Musical Manuscripts in the Bodleian Library Monumenti vaticani di paleografia musicale latina
